<p>For a lot of people who came online in the 1990s, finding your way around the web was less like asking a machine for an answer and more like wandering through a town built by enthusiasts. You clicked from page to page, followed lists of recommended links, opened category trees, read personal home pages, and slowly got a feel for where good material lived. The web was messy, but it was also surprisingly human. Somebody had to decide what belonged where. Somebody had to care enough to describe a site properly. Somebody had to think, “this is worth keeping”.</p>

<p>That is what made web directories so important. Before search engines grew into the giant systems we know today, directories were one of the main ways people discovered information online. They were not fast in the modern sense, and they were never complete, but they offered something that search alone has never really replaced: judgement. A directory did not simply tell you that a page existed. It gave you a rough sense that another person had seen it, categorised it, and considered it worth a visitor’s time.</p>

