<h2>What a web directory actually did</h2>
<p>A web directory was not just a big list of links. At its best, it was an attempt to organise the web in a way that made sense to an ordinary person. Sites were grouped by topic, then broken down into narrower and narrower subtopics, much like a library catalogue or a subject encyclopedia. If you were interested in astronomy, folk music, vintage computers, train timetables, or bird clubs, you did not necessarily begin by typing a phrase into a search box. You might instead browse into a subject tree and see what had already been gathered there.</p>

<p>This sounds quaint now, but it solved a very real problem. Early search tools were often rough. They might miss useful pages, produce strange results, or rank material in ways that felt arbitrary. A directory offered a calmer experience. If a category had been built properly, you could reach a useful cluster of sites without having to guess the right wording. You were not fighting an index. You were following a structure.</p>

<p>That structure mattered. A good category title could tell you a lot. A short editorial description beneath a link could tell you whether a site was scholarly, personal, commercial, historical, official, or simply interesting. In a world where websites varied wildly in quality, this small bit of context was extremely valuable.</p>

<h2>Why directories made sense in the early web</h2>
<p>The early web was small enough that human curation felt plausible. Not easy, but plausible. There was still a reasonable hope that if enough people contributed, useful territory could be mapped. The web also had a different character then. There were more static sites, more hobby pages, more institutional pages that changed slowly, and more independent publishers building things for the simple pleasure of putting them online. A directory could keep up, at least for a while, because the ground beneath it was not moving quite as quickly as it does now.</p>

<p>There was also a cultural fit. The early online world already had a tradition of curated lists. In the BBS era, sysops maintained file libraries, message areas, and text archives by hand. In the FTP era, administrators organised public directories, mirrors, and software collections with practical care. The idea that useful information should be arranged by people, rather than left entirely to automation, did not feel unusual. It felt responsible.</p>

<p>That is part of why directories and related systems sat so naturally alongside the early web. They grew out of the same mindset: communities of users helping other users find worthwhile material. If you browse this project’s <a href="<?= e(base_url('/pages/bulletin-board-systems')) ?>">BBS article</a> or the page on <a href="<?= e(base_url('/pages/ftp-archives-and-early-file-sharing')) ?>">FTP archives and early file sharing</a>, you can see the roots of that culture. The directory model did not appear from nowhere. It inherited a tradition of selection, stewardship, and practical organisation from the older networked world that came before the web exploded.</p>

<h2>The pleasure of browsing</h2>
<p>Search is efficient when you already know roughly what you want. Directories were often better when you did not. That is an important distinction, and one that has been partly lost.</p>

<p>If you typed a narrow question into a search engine, you hoped to be taken straight to an answer. But if you only had a broad curiosity, or wanted to get the lay of the land, browsing a directory could be much more rewarding. You might enter a category looking for one thing and come away with five better things. A neatly built subject tree encouraged discovery through proximity. Sites sat beside related sites. Topics connected to neighbouring topics. You learned not only from individual pages but from the editorial shape of the category itself.</p>

<p>That is one reason directories left such a strong impression on people who used them seriously. They did not only answer questions. They taught context. A category could reveal that a topic had subfields, historical branches, official bodies, fan communities, archives, and technical resources. It quietly educated the user while helping them browse.</p>

<p>Modern search engines can still do a version of this, but much of the experience has changed. Results are often flattened into a ranked list. Rich snippets, advertisements, shopping boxes, AI summaries, and optimisation tactics compete for attention. Browsing can feel less like exploring a landscape and more like sifting through a feed. That is not always bad. Search is astonishingly powerful. But it is a different kind of experience, and something was lost when browsing ceased to be central.</p>

<h2>What search engines did better</h2>
<p>It would be silly to pretend directories were superior in every way. They were not. Search engines won for good reasons, and many of those reasons were practical rather than philosophical.</p>

<p>The biggest reason was scale. As the web grew, manual curation became brutally hard. Every useful new category generated more work. Every site submission required review. Every dead link needed maintenance. Entire corners of the web could appear faster than volunteers or editorial teams could sensibly classify them. Search engines, by contrast, could crawl, index, and revisit huge numbers of pages automatically. Once ranking improved, especially with better link analysis and relevance models, search became too useful to ignore.</p>

<p>Search also handled specificity better. If you wanted a very particular phrase, error message, product model, or obscure reference, a directory was rarely the right tool. It might point you toward a good area, but it could not compete with a machine built to retrieve exact strings from vast indexes. Directories gave shape. Search gave reach.</p>

<p>There was another factor too: user expectations changed. Once people became accustomed to typing a few words and getting instant results, patience for browsing dropped. Search trained users to think in queries. Directories belonged to a slower, more attentive style of use.</p>

<h2>What search engines did not replace</h2>
<p>Even so, there are things that search engines never really replaced. The most obvious is editorial judgement. Search can estimate authority, popularity, freshness, location, and relevance signals. It cannot fully replicate the feeling of a knowledgeable human having looked at a site and said, “yes, this belongs here”.</p>

<p>This matters more than people sometimes realise. The web does not merely contain information. It contains noise, repetition, commercial padding, vanity pages, abandoned pages, scraped copies, manipulated rankings, and an endless amount of material that technically exists but is not especially helpful. Search engines try to sort that mess algorithmically, and often do a good job, but algorithmic ranking is not the same thing as curation. Popularity and usefulness overlap, but they are not identical. Neither are visibility and value.</p>

<p>Directories were often especially good in areas where quality mattered more than quantity. Niche hobbies. Local history. Specialist communities. Preserved technical documentation. Older resources that remained valuable but were no longer popular. Human editors could spot these things precisely because they were not merely counting links or measuring clicks. They were applying taste, subject familiarity, and a bit of care.</p>

<p>That is also why a directory like this one still makes sense. The aim is not to compete head-on with a modern search engine. That would be absurd. The aim is to preserve, organise, and surface historically meaningful material that can otherwise disappear into the background. When you browse the <a href="<?= e(base_url('/category/text-archives')) ?>">text archives</a>, follow the structure of the <a href="<?= e(base_url('/category')) ?>">directory categories</a>, or move from an article into a curated part of the site, you are using the web in a slightly older but often more thoughtful way.</p>

<h2>Yahoo, DMOZ, and the directory era</h2>
<p>The most famous web directories left a long shadow. Yahoo began as a hand-built guide to the web, and that origin story tells you a lot about the period. People were not just indexing the web. They were trying to make it legible. DMOZ, later known as the Open Directory Project, pushed the model further by relying on a large network of volunteer editors. Its ambition was enormous: organise the web through distributed human effort.</p>

<p>That approach had strengths and weaknesses. On the good days, it produced carefully structured categories and exposed worthwhile sites that might otherwise have been overlooked. On the bad days, it could be slow, inconsistent, and hard to scale. But even where it fell short, it represented a serious and important attempt to solve a cultural problem: how do you keep the web understandable as it grows?</p>

<p>Your own directory clearly belongs in that tradition, though with a much narrower and more achievable focus. That is probably a strength. The broad web became too large for one universal human directory, but specific historical or thematic areas can still benefit hugely from curation. The answer was never that directories were useless. The answer was that they work best when their scope and purpose are clear.</p>

<h2>Why directories faded</h2>
<p>Directories faded for a mix of reasons. Scale was the biggest. Commercial pressure was another. Once web discovery became tied to advertising, traffic, analytics, and search engine optimisation, the economics changed. Search was not only more scalable; it also fit better with the broader web economy that was emerging.</p>

<p>The changing nature of websites mattered too. Static sites gave way to dynamic content, endless updates, social feeds, video platforms, marketplaces, and systems that were harder to classify cleanly. Many sites no longer belonged neatly in one category. Others changed so often that descriptions became outdated almost immediately. A carefully maintained category tree struggled in a world where the web itself was becoming more fluid, more platform-based, and less stable.</p>

<p>There was also a subtle cultural shift. The early web rewarded patience, browsing, and curiosity. The later web increasingly rewarded speed, convenience, and scale. Search fit the newer culture better. It felt instant. It felt comprehensive. It felt objective, even when it was not.</p>

<h2>Why directories still matter now</h2>
<p>Strangely enough, many of the same conditions that made directories seem obsolete are now helping make them interesting again. The modern web is noisy. Search results can be cluttered. Valuable old material is often buried. Entire forms of knowledge, especially those outside commercial trends, are harder to stumble across than they should be. In that environment, a well-built directory can feel refreshing.</p>

<p>Not because it is bigger. Not because it is faster. Because it is selective.</p>

<p>A good directory gives a reader confidence that the links were chosen for a reason. It also encourages a healthier relationship with discovery. Instead of demanding the quickest answer every time, it invites the reader to look around, follow a trail, and build context. In historical subjects especially, that matters. You do not always understand an old technology or community by jumping straight to one result. Sometimes you need the surrounding material as well.</p>

<p>That is the real strength of the directory model in a project like this one. It is not nostalgia for its own sake. It is a practical response to a real problem: worthwhile material exists, but it is scattered, aging, and easy to miss. Human curation can still do useful work there.</p>

<h2>Directories and search are not enemies</h2>
<p>The most sensible view is not that directories should replace search engines, or that search engines somehow ruined the web on their own. The two models do different jobs. Search is excellent for retrieval at scale. Directories are excellent for context, curation, and guided discovery. In some of the best web projects, the two approaches complement each other.</p>

<p>You can already see the shape of that balance here. The directory structure helps users browse historically meaningful categories. The search function helps them retrieve specific things. The long-form pages provide narrative and orientation. The text archives preserve material that might otherwise remain hidden in a raw dump. None of these parts has to win against the others. They work together.</p>

<h2>The deeper point</h2>
<p>Underneath the technical argument lies a human one. A directory says that the web is not just a mass of pages to be indexed. It is also a body of work that can be arranged, understood, and handed on. It says that selection matters. That description matters. That context matters. That some sites are worth preserving even when they are no longer loud enough to rise naturally in modern search results.</p>

<p>That older attitude still has value. In some corners of the web, especially historical ones, it may be more valuable now than it was twenty years ago.</p>

